80
00:04:33.060 --> 00:04:35.380
One of the things that I find really useful when talking about...

81
00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:39.110
AI means a lot of different things to a lot of different people, and because it's

82
00:04:39.140 --> 00:04:41.280
such a hot topic and everybody wants to get their arms around it,

83
00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:44.400
everybody's going to define it a little bit differently.

84
00:04:44.660 --> 00:04:45.580
For me, personally,

85
00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:49.580
it makes it a lot easier when I think especially about regulation, if I break AI

86
00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:53.500
into three components. It's a training data set that you put together, and

87
00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:56.840
that might be something that you have locally, it might be something that you're

88
00:04:56.860 --> 00:05:00.700
collaborating with. There's an algorithm that is applied to that data set, whether

89
00:05:00.740 --> 00:05:03.780
it's a supervised learning, supervised machine learning algorithm, or something

90
00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:07.820
generative like an LLM. And then there's an interface that allows you

91
00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:11.390
to interact with that model. And so those are the kind of the three components, and

92
00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:14.140
I find it's easier to kind of talk about it when I think of it as those three

93
00:05:14.240 --> 00:05:17.800
parts. The kind of classic example these days is take all the text on the

94
00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:21.380
internet, stuff it into a transformer model, and then give some people access to a

95
00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:22.300
chatbot.

96
00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:27.130
The reason why this is, of course, a topic that has had a lot of attention at this

97
00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:30.580
AACR is two things are happening simultaneously.

98
00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:34.560
You can scale up the size of compute that is happening, and the kind of scale of

99
00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:37.080
models that you can build is dramatically increasing.

100
00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:41.350
We were just talking before that they keep saying there's going to be a plateau on

101
00:05:41.350 --> 00:05:44.000
these models, and there's no plateau. It just keeps going and going and going.

102
00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:48.200
And at the same time, the collection of different types of data is

103
00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:50.720
getting cheaper and cheaper, and so we're collecting more and more of it.

104
00:05:51.110 --> 00:05:55.060
This is the plot for genomics, but you can make the same exact graph for imaging or

105
00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:57.280
EHR data or really any other type of data.

106
00:05:57.320 --> 00:06:00.080
It's all down and to the right in terms of the cost of collecting

107
00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:03.392
data.I think most importantly, though, is the interface.

108
00:06:04.292 --> 00:06:06.052
Machine learning has been going on for a long time.

109
00:06:06.292 --> 00:06:07.772
There have been these models for a long time.

110
00:06:07.932 --> 00:06:10.952
I think that there's been a lot of innovation in how we interact with these models,

111
00:06:12.152 --> 00:06:15.842
whether it's something like a very general-purpose chatbot like Claude, something

112
00:06:15.852 --> 00:06:19.342
that's a little bit more bio-specific or health-specific, like OpenEvidence,

113
00:06:19.812 --> 00:06:22.732
or like the models that we build at the Synthesize Bio company that are foundation

114
00:06:22.752 --> 00:06:26.012
models for gene expression. All of these have very simple interfaces.

115
00:06:26.072 --> 00:06:29.952
You type in some text, it generates something back for you, and being able to

116
00:06:30.012 --> 00:06:33.612
interact with models is what I think is really driving a lot of the conversation

117
00:06:33.652 --> 00:06:34.212
that's happening.

118
00:06:35.472 --> 00:06:38.172
So I think there's actually... This should say four, so sorry about that.

119
00:06:38.292 --> 00:06:41.842
Already can't count. Four grand opportunities in AI for cancer.

120
00:06:42.332 --> 00:06:45.312
One is in care and operations, one is in drug discovery, one is in drug

121
00:06:45.352 --> 00:06:48.532
development, and one is in consumer health, and I think in all of these areas in

122
00:06:48.572 --> 00:06:51.852
these two roles, particularly in my role as chief data officer and professor,

123
00:06:52.412 --> 00:06:56.392
we're seeing impacts of AI across all of these and kind

124
00:06:56.412 --> 00:07:00.372
of racing to catch up with how we think about regulating them or setting up

125
00:07:00.452 --> 00:07:01.972
frameworks to being able to regulate them.

126
00:07:03.172 --> 00:07:04.472
I'm going to briefly touch on all four.

127
00:07:04.532 --> 00:07:05.492
Just since I'm first, I

128
00:07:06.632 --> 00:07:09.012
decided to zoom out and give a little bit of an overview, and then there'll be

129
00:07:09.172 --> 00:07:11.432
deeper dives on sort of drug development

130
00:07:12.232 --> 00:07:13.842
and discovery on the next couple of talks.

131
00:07:15.152 --> 00:07:18.732
In optimizing care and operations, this is where actually I think AI's had the most

132
00:07:18.772 --> 00:07:21.352
immediate and dramatic impact in the health system.

133
00:07:22.312 --> 00:07:26.252
And largely, that's because a lot of the things that you do there have

134
00:07:26.292 --> 00:07:28.112
different kinds of regulatory structures.

135
00:07:29.192 --> 00:07:33.152
Despite that, it's a really challenging space if you're a chief data officer or

136
00:07:33.192 --> 00:07:35.132
chief AI officer of a healthcare org right now.

137
00:07:35.252 --> 00:07:39.072
You're trying to evaluate how is the data that you are dealing with

138
00:07:39.172 --> 00:07:42.752
from your health system being used or not used in the tools you're interacting

139
00:07:42.792 --> 00:07:43.032
with.

140
00:07:44.312 --> 00:07:46.612
How do you decide which models to deploy,

141
00:07:47.452 --> 00:07:50.662
both for drug development but also just for clinical operations?

142
00:07:51.172 --> 00:07:55.092
And then how do you actually monitor and govern how those models are being used

143
00:07:55.112 --> 00:07:58.612
in practice? So to give you a really concrete example, you can think

144
00:07:58.652 --> 00:08:02.352
about the ways in which ambient listening is being deployed in

145
00:08:02.372 --> 00:08:05.852
clinical care right now. You have companies that offer services where they

146
00:08:06.352 --> 00:08:09.771
basically listen to the patient-doctor interaction, do voice-to-text,

147
00:08:10.192 --> 00:08:13.862
text to various different other things, and those are relatively

148
00:08:13.952 --> 00:08:17.812
lightly regulated. And so the question is: how do you think about, is this okay?

149
00:08:17.872 --> 00:08:18.712
Is it not okay?

150
00:08:19.752 --> 00:08:22.212
Does it feel like it's violating legal requirements?

151
00:08:22.272 --> 00:08:24.932
Is all pretty gray and a little fuzzy and a little bit hard to deal with.

152
00:08:24.972 --> 00:08:27.812
So in this area, it's a little bit less clear.

153
00:08:29.432 --> 00:08:32.072
The other one that I think is really interesting because there's been a lot of

154
00:08:32.092 --> 00:08:34.752
excitement recently. I don't know if people saw this, but a person

155
00:08:35.913 --> 00:08:39.252
using large language models and their own personal

156
00:08:39.293 --> 00:08:43.232
resources had diagnosed the cancer of their dog.

157
00:08:43.273 --> 00:08:45.332
I don't know if any of you saw this announcement.

158
00:08:45.762 --> 00:08:48.472
And then they actually did some experiments and then

159
00:08:49.412 --> 00:08:53.152
basically tried to cure their own dog of cancer from using LLMs and were quite

160
00:08:53.172 --> 00:08:55.972
successful, according to all the press around this story.

161
00:08:56.832 --> 00:08:57.412
But this is where,

162
00:08:58.512 --> 00:09:02.272
that's in dogs, but you could imagine that kind of thing is the

163
00:09:02.292 --> 00:09:03.952
potential of these models in humans, too.

164
00:09:03.992 --> 00:09:07.452
And so we have to really think through what does it mean to regulate drug discovery

165
00:09:07.532 --> 00:09:11.092
if anybody can do it. And so I think that it's a really important

166
00:09:12.172 --> 00:09:14.452
gap in how we think about how these things are regulated.

167
00:09:14.532 --> 00:09:16.482
Because, if that person's

168
00:09:17.912 --> 00:09:20.032
dog had died, that's of course tragic.

169
00:09:20.492 --> 00:09:24.192
But if people start saying, "I've discovered a new drug for something," and then it

170
00:09:24.212 --> 00:09:28.192
gets deployed to a lot of humans, that could be even more importantly

171
00:09:28.432 --> 00:09:28.952
challenging.

172
00:09:30.652 --> 00:09:34.512
In drug development, I think that there's actually a split, and I'll let

