00:09:34.532 --> 00:09:37.072
others talk a lot more about this who have more experience in the area.

174
00:09:37.132 --> 00:09:40.932
But my personal experience in it is there's a real split between supervised and

175
00:09:40.972 --> 00:09:44.552
generative models. For supervised models, I actually feel like the

176
00:09:44.572 --> 00:09:46.812
regulatory pathway is pretty well...

177
00:09:47.072 --> 00:09:50.572
There's still work to be done, but there's a lot of development that's been put in

178
00:09:50.592 --> 00:09:54.572
place. For generative models, it's much more unclear how you

179
00:09:54.592 --> 00:09:57.232
regulate how a generative model is going to work.

180
00:09:57.252 --> 00:10:01.192
And what I mean by that is if that model isn't just doing a specific task but

181
00:10:01.272 --> 00:10:05.182
has a broad collection of use cases, understanding how does

182
00:10:05.212 --> 00:10:07.212
that model work for those specific use cases?

183
00:10:07.292 --> 00:10:11.032
How do you put a barrier around those use cases and then regulate

184
00:10:11.092 --> 00:10:15.012
that? Is something that I think is a pretty tricky problem, and although

185
00:10:15.032 --> 00:10:18.632
there's really great guidance that has been coming out, and draft guidance that's

186
00:10:18.672 --> 00:10:22.552
been coming out from the FDA, some of that kind of is a little bit more challenging

187
00:10:22.572 --> 00:10:25.392
when you get to the sort of generative components of these models.

188
00:10:26.932 --> 00:10:30.852
And then the last one that we're seeing a lot of is, there was a time

189
00:10:30.872 --> 00:10:34.692
where there was Dr. Google. You came in to see your provider, and you asked

190
00:10:34.732 --> 00:10:36.132
Google questions about your health.

191
00:10:37.072 --> 00:10:40.832
Dr. GPT is now the thing, and so people come in, and they have already

192
00:10:40.912 --> 00:10:44.692
talked to Claude or a GPT model or

193
00:10:44.832 --> 00:10:48.532
Google Gemini or one of these other models, and they've asked a lot of questions.

194
00:10:49.232 --> 00:10:52.612
And they've uploaded their whole patient record to this modeling system.

195
00:10:53.872 --> 00:10:55.702
Sometimes it provides really great information.

196
00:10:56.112 --> 00:10:59.312
Sometimes it provides a lot of comfort to patients who can't get access to health

197
00:10:59.352 --> 00:11:00.722
providers as much as they would like.

198
00:11:01.212 --> 00:11:04.912
At the same time, there can also be pretty tragic consequences if they get

199
00:11:04.982 --> 00:11:08.552
misinformation or that information isn't completely well-characterized.

200
00:11:08.572 --> 00:11:12.202
And so in this space, and I think in all of the spaces,

201
00:11:12.852 --> 00:11:16.792
we don't really fully understand what is the surface of

202
00:11:16.832 --> 00:11:20.182
where these models work very well and where these models don't work very well, and

203
00:11:20.272 --> 00:11:23.972
that difference can be critical for using these

204
00:11:24.012 --> 00:11:27.312
models in practice. And so I think these are four areas where I

205
00:11:27.332 --> 00:11:30.932
think my personal belief is that AI will have major

206
00:11:30.992 --> 00:11:34.952
impacts on all four of these areas and major positive impacts, but there are

207
00:11:34.972 --> 00:11:37.112
some challenges that remain in how do we regulate them.

208
00:11:37.142 --> 00:11:40.972
And I think for somebody who has to set an AI strategy for a whole healthcare

209
00:11:41.032 --> 00:11:44.692
org that includes clinical trials and includes healthcare, it includes research,

210
00:11:45.342 --> 00:11:48.912
the really challenging thing is that the AI regulatory environment is a bit

