00:11:53.432 --> 00:11:54.932
And of course, this is one person's opinion.

213
00:11:55.012 --> 00:11:58.812
I'm not representing the opinion of the Fred Hutch or Synthesize Bio in stating

214
00:11:58.852 --> 00:12:01.832
whether something's emerging or not. This is Jeff Leek's opinion.

215
00:12:02.422 --> 00:12:05.922
There are some areas where it feels like the regulation is very clear, and you can

216
00:12:05.932 --> 00:12:08.872
really use it, and that means you can move really, really quickly.

217
00:12:08.882 --> 00:12:12.292
And then there are other places where it's pretty unclear, and it's still being

218
00:12:12.312 --> 00:12:14.892
developed, and it means it's much harder to move quickly.

219
00:12:14.932 --> 00:12:18.312
And so the challenge, I think, for all of us is that these models are

220
00:12:18.352 --> 00:12:22.152
developing at a speed that makes it really hard to

221
00:12:22.192 --> 00:12:25.012
know how to evaluate them and make good decisions about

222
00:12:25.032 --> 00:12:29.006
them.So, a couple of opportunities I think we can

223
00:12:29.056 --> 00:12:32.656
fill collaboratively at the intersection of industry, academics,

224
00:12:32.716 --> 00:12:36.636
and government are four areas. One is these

225
00:12:36.676 --> 00:12:39.736
models are going to become more complicated, and I'm stealing a little thunder

226
00:12:39.756 --> 00:12:41.195
here. This is actually George's idea.

227
00:12:41.456 --> 00:12:44.866
He's going to talk a lot more about this, but I'm going to say that I agree that

228
00:12:45.016 --> 00:12:47.376
benchmarks are an incredibly important component of this.

229
00:12:47.436 --> 00:12:51.316
Like, the models are going to get more complicated, so we can't rely on

230
00:12:51.356 --> 00:12:54.476
them being interpretable. Like, if you have a trillion-parameter model, you're

231
00:12:54.486 --> 00:12:57.156
never going to be able to interpret it. So how do you evaluate it?

232
00:12:57.196 --> 00:12:59.776
