536
00:30:40.626 --> 00:30:43.466
applied to dose optimization and pharmacovigilance as well.

537
00:30:44.646 --> 00:30:48.486
I want to clarify one important scoping point, and it's kind of been brought up a

538
00:30:48.526 --> 00:30:52.106
little bit. FDA's perspective on AI for drugs and

539
00:30:52.126 --> 00:30:55.466
biologicsWhich was shown in this January

540
00:30:55.546 --> 00:30:58.776
2025 draft guidance, which I'll explore in more detail.

541
00:30:59.706 --> 00:31:03.666
It's focused specifically on AI used to produce data and information

542
00:31:04.086 --> 00:31:07.666
to support regulatory decision-making regarding safety,

543
00:31:08.086 --> 00:31:09.666
effectiveness, and quality for drugs.

544
00:31:10.066 --> 00:31:13.646
It explicitly does not cover drug discovery, and it does not cover

545
00:31:13.656 --> 00:31:17.446
purely operational uses of AI, such as drafting a regulatory

546
00:31:17.546 --> 00:31:20.336
submission or allocating internal resources.

547
00:31:20.926 --> 00:31:24.786
And so those things don't affect the patient safety or study reliability, so

548
00:31:24.826 --> 00:31:27.286
that's not so much of a concern for us at the FDA.

549
00:31:30.006 --> 00:31:32.946
So our regulatory approach isn't theoretical.

550
00:31:32.986 --> 00:31:36.586
It's grounded in real experience reviewing AI regulatory submissions.

551
00:31:37.426 --> 00:31:41.186
Through 2024, CDER's received 800 submissions that include

552
00:31:41.246 --> 00:31:45.146
AI, and when you add in CBER, that number exceeds over 1,000.

553
00:31:45.906 --> 00:31:47.306
The growth has been dramatic.

554
00:31:48.246 --> 00:31:51.806
It started as a handful of submissions annually before

555
00:31:51.926 --> 00:31:55.366
2021 to 307 in 2024 alone.

556
00:31:56.466 --> 00:32:00.226
And oncology consistently represents the largest share of AI-containing

557
00:32:00.266 --> 00:32:04.086
submissions across the therapeutic areas at about 27% of the total.

558
00:32:05.606 --> 00:32:07.466
The use cases we're seeing are diverse.

559
00:32:07.766 --> 00:32:11.286
In oncology specifically, they include patient selection and outcome prediction,

560
00:32:11.926 --> 00:32:15.906
confounding adjustment, pharmacometric modeling, use of external control

561
00:32:15.966 --> 00:32:19.796
arms, and post-marketing surveillance using natural language processing.

562
00:32:20.426 --> 00:32:24.286
The breadth of the applications is exactly why we need a framework flexible

563
00:32:24.346 --> 00:32:26.926
enough to accommodate very different types of AI use.

564
00:32:28.466 --> 00:32:31.546
Our framework also didn't emerge in isolation.

565
00:32:31.786 --> 00:32:35.636
It was shaped by years of collaborative engagement, workshops, expert

566
00:32:35.686 --> 00:32:36.306
convenings,

567
00:32:37.206 --> 00:32:41.186
the establishment of an AI council, policy working group, community of practice,

568
00:32:41.206 --> 00:32:45.106
and interest groups within FDA, and ongoing tracking of AI

569
00:32:45.166 --> 00:32:46.706
uses in regulatory submissions.

570
00:32:47.566 --> 00:32:50.906
All of that culminated in the publication of draft guidance documents in January

571
00:32:51.026 --> 00:32:51.766
2025.

572
00:32:53.126 --> 00:32:56.866
So for this draft guidance, considerations for the use

573
00:32:56.966 --> 00:33:00.816
of artificial intelligence to support regulatory decision-making for drug and

574
00:33:00.866 --> 00:33:01.845
biologics products,

575
00:33:03.326 --> 00:33:05.426
it's organized around three main areas.

576
00:33:06.246 --> 00:33:09.946
Risk-based credibility assessment framework, special considerations for

577
00:33:10.046 --> 00:33:13.826
lifecycle maintenance of AI model credibility, and

578
00:33:13.966 --> 00:33:16.026
options for early engagement with the agency.

579
00:33:18.006 --> 00:33:21.956
So to make the framework concrete, I'm going

580
00:33:21.966 --> 00:33:25.116
to walk through an example, and this one is directly relevant to oncology.

581
00:33:25.926 --> 00:33:29.486
And this is actually the first example that's provided within the draft guidance.

582
00:33:30.226 --> 00:33:33.546
Drug A is under development and is associated with a life-threatening

583
00:33:33.626 --> 00:33:37.406
drug-related adverse event. In previous trials, all

584
00:33:37.446 --> 00:33:40.806
patients underwent 24 hours of inpatient monitoring after

585
00:33:40.826 --> 00:33:43.686
dosing because of concerns of this potential reaction.

586
00:33:44.266 --> 00:33:47.386
But data from those trials showed that some patients were actually at low risk.

587
00:33:47.946 --> 00:33:51.746
In a new study, the sponsor wants to use an AI model to identify which

588
00:33:51.786 --> 00:33:55.546
patients are at low risk and send those participants

589
00:33:55.606 --> 00:33:58.786
home for outpatient monitoring instead of keeping them in the inpatient setting.

590
00:33:59.676 --> 00:34:03.546
This is a realistic scenario in oncology, where toxicity management is central to

591
00:34:03.566 --> 00:34:06.886
trial design and where the stakes of misclassification are high.

592
00:34:07.846 --> 00:34:09.966
I'll use this example to walk through our framework.

593
00:34:11.066 --> 00:34:13.966
So the framework consists of seven steps.

594
00:34:14.026 --> 00:34:17.266
Let me walk through the first three using our example, then I'll describe the

595
00:34:17.286 --> 00:34:18.596
remaining steps more briefly.

596
00:34:19.406 --> 00:34:22.586
Step one is to define the question of interest.

597
00:34:22.616 --> 00:34:26.406
The specific question, decision, or concern the AI model is being used to

598
00:34:26.415 --> 00:34:30.346
address. In our example, the question is: What participants can be

599
00:34:30.386 --> 00:34:34.187
considered low risk and do not need inpatient monitoring after

600
00:34:34.207 --> 00:34:34.596
dosing?

601
00:34:35.946 --> 00:34:38.286
Step two is to define the context of use.

602
00:34:38.806 --> 00:34:42.707
The context of use describes the specific role and scope of the AI model.

603
00:34:43.506 --> 00:34:47.286
In this case, the COU is using the AI

604
00:34:47.326 --> 00:34:50.546
model to predict a patient's risk for a potentially

605
00:34:50.647 --> 00:34:54.466
life-threatening adverse event to drug A based on baseline

606
00:34:54.506 --> 00:34:58.286
characteristics and lab values. The model will stratify the clinical

607
00:34:58.366 --> 00:35:01.606
trial participants or patients into low versus high-risk

608
00:35:02.046 --> 00:35:06.036
groups and will be the sole determinant of whether patients require inpatient or

609
00:35:06.086 --> 00:35:07.656
outpatient monitoring after dosing.

610
00:35:08.526 --> 00:35:12.306
Step three is to assess the model risk, which is the conceptual heart of the

611
00:35:12.326 --> 00:35:15.846
framework, and so I'll spend a little bit of time here.

612
00:35:15.906 --> 00:35:19.826
So model risk is the possibility that the AI model output may lead to

613
00:35:19.836 --> 00:35:22.706
an incorrect decision that could result in an adverse outcome.

614
00:35:23.406 --> 00:35:25.806
Importantly, it is not the risk intrinsic to the model.

615
00:35:26.416 --> 00:35:29.916
Model risk is defined by two independently determined factors,

616
00:35:30.486 --> 00:35:33.206
model influence and decision consequence.

617
00:35:34.606 --> 00:35:38.316
Model influence, which is shown across the x-axis, is the contribution

618
00:35:38.346 --> 00:35:42.306
of AI model's output relative to other evidence used to

619
00:35:42.386 --> 00:35:45.876
answer the question of interest. In our example, the AI model is the sole

620
00:35:45.886 --> 00:35:48.566
determinant of which type of monitoring a patient receives.

621
00:35:49.266 --> 00:35:51.226
There's no other evidence being used in parallel.

622
00:35:51.326 --> 00:35:54.086
So in this example, the model influence is high.

623
00:35:54.866 --> 00:35:58.286
Decision consequence, which is shown along the y-axis, is the

624
00:35:58.346 --> 00:36:01.766
significance of an adverse outcome if the AI model gets it wrong.

625
00:36:02.346 --> 00:36:06.146
If patients who actually need inpatient monitoring are misclassified as low

626
00:36:06.206 --> 00:36:09.646
risk and sent home, they could experience a life-threatening adverse

627
00:36:09.706 --> 00:36:12.046
reaction without access to appropriate treatment.

628
00:36:12.466 --> 00:36:13.906
Decision consequence is high.

629
00:36:14.906 --> 00:36:18.846
Therefore, the model risk for this COU is high, and that matters because

630
00:36:18.886 --> 00:36:22.586
the level and stringency of credibility evidence, which is the

631
00:36:22.646 --> 00:36:26.526
purposes of step four through seven, is calibrated to that risk

632
00:36:26.566 --> 00:36:26.906
level.

633
00:36:27.866 --> 00:36:31.466
One thing to consider is that humans in the loops could help moderate this risk.

634
00:36:34.146 --> 00:36:37.586
What we ask for in terms of this credibility evidence is

635
00:36:37.626 --> 00:36:40.786
commensurate with model risk and tailored to the specific context of

636
00:36:40.866 --> 00:36:44.306
use. For a high-risk model, we'll ask for greater

637
00:36:44.366 --> 00:36:44.896
oversight,

638
00:36:45.746 --> 00:36:48.906
more stringent performance acceptance criteria, more detailed

639
00:36:48.946 --> 00:36:52.466
documentation, more rigorous credibility assessment activities,

640
00:36:52.926 --> 00:36:55.186
and more robust risk mitigation strategies.

641
00:36:55.806 --> 00:36:59.778
For a low-risk modelSay an AI tool used to flag potential

642
00:36:59.818 --> 00:37:03.598
data entry errors in a clinical database where a human reviews

643
00:37:03.638 --> 00:37:06.778
every flag, we would likely ask for much less.

644
00:37:07.678 --> 00:37:10.198
One thing to note, this isn't a one-size-fits-all framework.

645
00:37:10.238 --> 00:37:13.718
It's designed to be proportionate, and that proportionality is what makes it

646
00:37:13.758 --> 00:37:17.498
applicable across the enormous diversity of AI uses we are and will

647
00:37:17.558 --> 00:37:20.258
continue to see in oncology submissions.

648
00:37:22.258 --> 00:37:26.018
Continuing through the rest of the steps, step four is to develop a

649
00:37:26.038 --> 00:37:30.018
credibility assessment plan. So this plan describes how you establish that the

650
00:37:30.058 --> 00:37:33.718
AI model output is credible for the specific

651
00:37:33.758 --> 00:37:37.648
COU. It should describe the model itself, the data used to develop it, and

652
00:37:37.698 --> 00:37:39.948
how the model was trained and evaluated.

653
00:37:40.538 --> 00:37:44.247
Critically, this is actually the step where we strongly encourage sponsors to come

654
00:37:44.278 --> 00:37:48.258
in to talk to us. Early engagement with the FDA before a sponsor

655
00:37:48.338 --> 00:37:52.138
executes a plan can save significant time and resources by aligning

656
00:37:52.198 --> 00:37:56.058
expectations up front. Step five is then to execute the plan, and this

657
00:37:56.078 --> 00:37:58.518
is ideally before that early engagement.

658
00:37:59.118 --> 00:38:02.868
Step six is to document the results in a credibility assessment report.

659
00:38:03.368 --> 00:38:05.918
And that includes any deviations from the plan.

660
00:38:06.218 --> 00:38:10.038
This report may be submitted as part of regulatory submission included in a

661
00:38:10.058 --> 00:38:13.938
meeting package or held by the sponsor and made available to

662
00:38:13.998 --> 00:38:16.958
FDA on request, for example, during an inspection.

663
00:38:17.798 --> 00:38:21.618
The appropriate approach depends on the COU and should be discussed with FDA.

664
00:38:22.398 --> 00:38:26.118
Finally, step seven is to determine whether the AI model is adequate for the COU.

665
00:38:26.818 --> 00:38:30.278
If credibility is not sufficiently established, there are several options.

666
00:38:30.318 --> 00:38:33.808
The sponsor can reduce model influence by incorporating additional evidence,

667
00:38:34.438 --> 00:38:38.118
increase the rigor of the credibility assessment, add development

668
00:38:38.198 --> 00:38:41.858
data, or revise the context of use. Again, this is an iterative process.

669
00:38:41.898 --> 00:38:43.158
It's not a pass/fail gate.

670
00:38:44.878 --> 00:38:48.818
A question that arises in oncology, what happens when the AI

671
00:38:48.878 --> 00:38:52.678
tool itself is a medical device? If an AI model meets the

672
00:38:52.718 --> 00:38:56.478
statutory definition of a device, for example, a computational pathology

673
00:38:56.518 --> 00:39:00.358
tool that analyzes whole slide images to aid in clinical diagnosis, which

674
00:39:00.418 --> 00:39:04.088
we're going to talk about, which George referred to, or a

675
00:39:04.118 --> 00:39:07.758
radiomics platform that assesses treatment response, that's

676
00:39:07.838 --> 00:39:11.658
subject to a separate regulatory framework

677
00:39:12.018 --> 00:39:15.938
for AI-enabled devices, which is based on, among other guidances, the

678
00:39:15.948 --> 00:39:19.788
draft guidance, Artificial Intelligence-Enabled Device Software Functions:

679
00:39:20.338 --> 00:39:22.898
Lifecycle Management and Marketing Submission Recommendations.

680
00:39:23.338 --> 00:39:26.848
That was also published in January 2025 on the same day as

681
00:39:26.898 --> 00:39:30.698
the drug and biologics guidance. This guidance, the device

682
00:39:30.738 --> 00:39:34.178
guidance, covers a full total product life cycle from development through

683
00:39:34.188 --> 00:39:37.878
post-marketing monitoring and includes specific recommendations on

684
00:39:37.938 --> 00:39:41.258
device description, labeling, data management, performance

685
00:39:41.338 --> 00:39:45.218
validation, and cybersecurity. So the advice to

686
00:39:45.258 --> 00:39:49.228
any sponsors who are developing an AI tool that may be used in drug development,

687
00:39:50.158 --> 00:39:54.098
you need to determine early on if the tool meets the device definition.

688
00:39:56.398 --> 00:39:56.878
Model

689
00:39:57.778 --> 00:39:58.898
risk. Sorry.

690
00:40:00.098 --> 00:40:04.058
So both of the guidance documents are actually grounded in this idea of the

691
00:40:04.098 --> 00:40:07.938
total product life cycle. This means that regulatory considerations begin at the

692
00:40:07.958 --> 00:40:11.458
design phase and extend through post-market monitoring and ultimately

693
00:40:11.498 --> 00:40:14.058
decommissioning. For oncology

694
00:40:14.938 --> 00:40:16.058
AI specifically,

695
00:40:16.858 --> 00:40:20.598
this is important implications, which we'll discuss in the questions, but

696
00:40:21.518 --> 00:40:25.078
data drift, the degradation of model performance when real-world

697
00:40:25.418 --> 00:40:29.027
inputs differ from training data, that's a particular concern in

698
00:40:29.058 --> 00:40:32.798
oncology because the standard of care is often changing so

699
00:40:32.838 --> 00:40:36.658
rapidly. New drug approvals, updated treatment guidelines, and shifting

700
00:40:36.718 --> 00:40:40.438
patient populations can affect how a model performs in deployment.

701
00:40:40.958 --> 00:40:44.738
So life cycle maintenance of AI model credibility is not

702
00:40:44.798 --> 00:40:48.278
optional. It's actually really a core regulatory expectation.

703
00:40:49.778 --> 00:40:52.378
I just want to also take a moment to talk about

704
00:40:53.278 --> 00:40:55.408
these 10 principles across AI life cycle.

705
00:40:56.378 --> 00:40:59.348
CDER and CBER, in collaboration with the EMA,

706
00:41:00.038 --> 00:41:03.768
developed 10 guiding principles for AI use in drug and biologic development,

707
00:41:04.238 --> 00:41:07.038
and this was published in January of this year, 2026.

708
00:41:07.638 --> 00:41:11.478
This work reflects a shared international commitment to responsible

709
00:41:11.538 --> 00:41:13.158
AI adoption in drug development.

710
00:41:14.358 --> 00:41:17.358
AI can accelerate innovation, reduce time to market,

711
00:41:17.997 --> 00:41:21.708
strengthen pharmacovigilance, and improve prediction of safety and efficacy,

712
00:41:22.198 --> 00:41:23.778
but only if it's used responsibly.

713
00:41:24.438 --> 00:41:27.868
Unlike traditional tools, AI systems evolve and interact with humans,

714
00:41:28.418 --> 00:41:32.018
which introduces new risks that require structured oversight.

715
00:41:32.898 --> 00:41:33.838
These principles aren't

716
00:41:35.198 --> 00:41:39.138
prescriptive rules. Rather, they're meant to inform good practice and support

717
00:41:39.178 --> 00:41:42.908
further guidance and harmonization among different regulatory agencies.

718
00:41:44.378 --> 00:41:47.958
So I want to highlight four key principles that I think are especially important to

719
00:41:47.998 --> 00:41:49.678
this audience and for our discussion.

720
00:41:50.918 --> 00:41:54.238
First, transparency in model development and

721
00:41:54.278 --> 00:41:58.168
decision-making processes. FDA does not require full

722
00:41:58.218 --> 00:42:01.878
explainability of every model. We recognize that complex deep learning

723
00:42:01.958 --> 00:42:05.498
models may not be fully interpretable in a way that is meaningful to end

724
00:42:05.598 --> 00:42:09.278
users. However, we do require methodological

725
00:42:09.378 --> 00:42:11.778
transparency, which I'll describe shortly.

726
00:42:12.558 --> 00:42:16.178
Second, external validation using independent representative data sets.

727
00:42:16.278 --> 00:42:19.738
We've talked about this, I think in George's presentation, he mentions this.

728
00:42:20.398 --> 00:42:23.398
Test data must be independent of development data.

729
00:42:23.818 --> 00:42:27.558
It must be representative of the intended use population, including across relevant

730
00:42:27.618 --> 00:42:30.548
demographic subgroups, cancer subtypes, and

731
00:42:31.678 --> 00:42:32.498
disease stages.

732
00:42:33.498 --> 00:42:35.978
Third, alignment with good machine learning practices.

733
00:42:36.558 --> 00:42:40.198
These are internationally recognized guiding principles that FDA has endorsed,

734
00:42:40.398 --> 00:42:44.018
and they provide a useful baseline for any AI development program.

735
00:42:44.938 --> 00:42:47.558
Fourth, early communication with FDA is

736
00:42:47.598 --> 00:42:49.118
encouraged.

737
00:42:50.178 --> 00:42:52.778
There are a number of regulatory challenges to consider.

738
00:42:53.338 --> 00:42:55.238
The first is bias and representativeness.

739
00:42:55.828 --> 00:42:59.058
The performance of an AI model depends heavily on the quality,

740
00:42:59.218 --> 00:43:03.118
diversity, and representativeness of the data used to train and tune

741
00:43:03.158 --> 00:43:06.170
it.In oncology, this is particularly acute.

742
00:43:06.790 --> 00:43:08.750
Training data sets may underrepresent

743
00:43:10.570 --> 00:43:14.460
certain demographic groups, cancer subtypes, disease

744
00:43:14.470 --> 00:43:18.430
stages, and because oncology standards of care evolve so rapidly, a

745
00:43:18.450 --> 00:43:21.170
model trained on historical data may

746
00:43:21.510 --> 00:43:25.470
perform poorly

747
00:43:25.490 --> 00:43:28.210
on patients treated under current protocols.

748
00:43:28.810 --> 00:43:31.810
So this is data drift, as I mentioned before, and it's a serious concern.

749
00:43:32.530 --> 00:43:36.310
For drugs and biologics, our guidance emphasizes that data used to develop

750
00:43:36.410 --> 00:43:40.190
AI models should be fit for use, meaning both relevant and

751
00:43:40.210 --> 00:43:42.230
reliable. These data should include

752
00:43:42.330 --> 00:43:46.250
key data elements and sufficient number

753
00:43:46.290 --> 00:43:50.050
of representative participants that reflect the target patient

754
00:43:50.090 --> 00:43:53.580
population. A second challenge is transparency and

755
00:43:53.630 --> 00:43:57.300
explainability. So this is an important distinction between

756
00:43:57.310 --> 00:44:01.090
interpretability, the degree to which cause and effect can be understood

757
00:44:01.130 --> 00:44:04.610
within a model, and explainability, the ability to

758
00:44:04.630 --> 00:44:08.210
provide explicit justifications for model decisions.

759
00:44:08.790 --> 00:44:12.220
As stated previously, FDA does not require full explainability,

760
00:44:12.830 --> 00:44:15.900
but instead requires methodological transparency.

761
00:44:16.450 --> 00:44:19.790
And that is the clear description of how a model was developed,

762
00:44:20.330 --> 00:44:23.220
what data were used, and how performance was evaluated.

763
00:44:24.020 --> 00:44:27.120
That should hopefully be achievable for any model, regardless of its

764
00:44:27.150 --> 00:44:28.790
complexity.

765
00:44:29.750 --> 00:44:33.140
The third challenge is data infrastructure, and I hope we're going to discuss some

766
00:44:33.150 --> 00:44:36.730
of this during our talk, but standardization of clinical data across

767
00:44:36.750 --> 00:44:39.010
institutions remains inconsistent.

768
00:44:39.050 --> 00:44:42.850
Questions of data ownership, privacy, and security are unresolved, and the

769
00:44:42.910 --> 00:44:46.610
field lacks public available reference data sets for benchmarking

770
00:44:46.690 --> 00:44:50.490
AI models in oncology, something that we believe is urgently needed.

771
00:44:51.950 --> 00:44:55.590
Just in terms of some path forwards, again, engage

772
00:44:55.650 --> 00:44:56.650
early with the FDA.

773
00:44:58.090 --> 00:45:01.130
Ensure robust validation across representative populations,

774
00:45:02.330 --> 00:45:05.050
which we've talked about. Implement real-world

775
00:45:06.270 --> 00:45:07.360
performance monitoring.

776
00:45:08.450 --> 00:45:10.870
Model deployment is not the finish line.

777
00:45:10.890 --> 00:45:14.260
Build monitoring into your development plan from the beginning and establish clear

778
00:45:14.350 --> 00:45:17.910
triggers for when model performance requires reassessing or retraining.

779
00:45:18.850 --> 00:45:22.790
Maintain transparency in model development and limitations.

780
00:45:23.310 --> 00:45:26.550
Document your choices, your data, your training processes, and your known

781
00:45:27.250 --> 00:45:28.330
failure modes.

782
00:45:29.230 --> 00:45:32.920
This is actually what helps us at the FDA evaluate the model's credibility,

783
00:45:33.410 --> 00:45:35.910
and it's what allows clinicians and patients to trust it.

784
00:45:36.310 --> 00:45:40.170
And then finally, establish multidisciplinary teams consisting of

785
00:45:40.710 --> 00:45:44.370
across the board people that would be involved in building these AI models and

786
00:45:44.430 --> 00:45:47.960
using them. And then regarding ongoing needs,

787
00:45:48.659 --> 00:45:52.130
this needs to be further development of public reference data sets for

788
00:45:52.170 --> 00:45:55.750
oncology AI validation, continued harmonization

789
00:45:56.610 --> 00:46:00.290
